.TH "KZ-INSTALL.SH" "5" "4.2.1" "kz" "File format"

.SH NAME
kz-install.sh - installation file for use with kz install

.SH SYNOPSIS
.SY kz-install.sh
.YS

.SH DESCRIPTION
This file contains commands to process as an installation file with kz install.
.br
Commands containing personal information, such as a username, are included in
an GPG-encrypted installation file, kz-install.sh.gpg.
.sp
The installation file contains so-called \fBapp-\fR, \fBdesc-\fR, \fBhost-\fR
and \fBcommand record\fRs.
.sp
The \fBapp record\fR indicates for which app the commands should be executed,
the \fBdesc record\fR provides a description of the app, and the
\fBhost record\fR indicates on which computers the commands should be executed.
.br
These records are followed by one or more records with commands, the
\fBcommand record\fRs.
.sp
See \fBTable 1\fR which \fBtypes\fR of records there are and how these records
are processed.
.sp
See \fBTable 2\fR for an \fBexample\fR of these records and how these records
are processed.
.br
More examples can be seen through the \fBkz install --browse\fR and
\fBkz install --cat\fR commands.
.LP
.B Table 1. Record types and their processing
.TS
allbox tab(:);
lb | lb.
T{
Regel
T}:T{
Description
T}
.T&
l | l
l | l.
T{
# INSTALL <app>
T}:T{
Which app to install (\fBapp-rule\fR), will be processed.
T}
T{
# DESC    <desc>
T}:T{
A description of the app (\fBdesc-rule\fR), will be processed.
T}
T{
# HOST    <host>
T}:T{
On which computers the app should be installed (\fBhost-rule\fR), will be
processed.
T}
T{
Command
T}:T{
Install app command (one or more \fBcommand record\fRs), will be executed.
T}
T{
T}:T{
Empty line (none, one or more), will be skipped.
T}
T{
# REMOVE  <app>
T}:T{
Remove the app (\fBapp-rule\fR for option \fB-r\fR, \fB--remove\fR), will be
processed.
.br
The description and computers are taken from the previous '# INSTALL <app>'
line.
T}
T{
Command
T}:T{
Remove app command (one or more \fBcommand record\fRs), will be executed.
T}
T{
T}:T{
T}
T{
# Comment
T}:T{
Comment line (none, one or more), will be skipped.
T}
.TE
.LP
.B Table 2. Example of records and their processing
.TS
box tab(:);
lb | lb.
T{
Record
T}:T{
Description
T}
.T&
- | -
l | l
l | l.
T{
# INSTALL calibre
T}:T{
Install calibre.
T}
T{
# DESC    Powerful and easy to use e-book manager.
T}:T{
Description of calibre.
T}
T{
# HOST    *
T}:T{
Install calibre on every computer, see [1].
T}
T{
sudo apt-get install --assume-yes calibre
T}:T{
Install command for calibre.
T}
T{
T}:T{
T}
T{
# REMOVE  calibre
T}:T{
Remove calibre.
T}
T{
sudo apt-get remove --assume-yes calibre
T}:T{
Remove command for calibre.
T}
.TE
.sp
[1]
.br
The line with '*' causes the associated commands to run on all computers.
.sp
A line with 'pc01' ensures that the associated commands are executed only on
host pc01 by default.
.br
A line with 'pc01 pc02' ensures that the associated commands are executed
only on pc01 and pc02 by default.
.br
A line with '#none' ensures that the associated commands are not executed on
a computer by default (NOTE: '#none' is not a valid computername and will
therefore never be selected by default).
.br
The app can still be installed on another computer with the command 'kz install
<app>', e.g. 'kz install calibre'.
.sp

.SH EXAMPLES
.EX
# INSTALL calibre
# DESC    Powerful and easy to use e-book manager.
# HOST    pc06
if grep --quiet --regexp='debian' /etc/os-release; then sudo apt-get install -\
-assume-yes calibre; fi
#
if grep --quiet --regexp='rhel\\|fedora' /etc/os-release; then sudo --validate\
 && wget --output-document=- https://download.calibre-ebook.com/linux-installe\
r.sh | sudo sh; fi

# REMOVE calibre
if grep --quiet --regexp='debian' /etc/os-release; then sudo apt-get remove --\
assume-yes calibre; fi
#
if grep --quiet --regexp='rhel\\|fedora' /etc/os-release; then sudo calibre-un\
install; fi
.EE

.SH SEE ALSO
\fBkz-install\fR(1),
\fBkz-install.sh.gpg\fR(5)
